{"timestamp": "2025-12-04 19:30:31.839355", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Troubleshooting Diagnosis Report\n\nSummary\n- Detected multiple connectivity anomalies across the SDN spine–leaf fabric.\n- Primary issues: incorrect OpenFlow programming on the leaf switches (leaf_1 and leaf_2), inconsistent with the actual topology and host-facing ports. This isolates hosts and breaks L2 forwarding.\n- Root cause: SDN controller misprogramming/stale/incorrect topology view leading to wrong flow entries; additionally, leaf_1 has an explicit all-traffic drop flow.\n\nObserved Symptoms\n- Host reachability:\n  - host_1_1 -> host_1_2 and host_2_1: 100% loss, “Destination Host Unreachable” from 10.0.0.1 (indicates ARP/Layer-2 failure on leaf_1 path).\n  - host_2_1 <-> host_2_2 (same leaf): 100% loss.\n- ARP state:\n  - host_1_1 and host_1_2: ip neigh shows FAILED for all peers (ARP requests not succeeding across leaf_1).\n  - host_2_1 and host_2_2: ip neigh shows STALE for each other and for 10.0.0.15/16 MACs; despite entries, no L2 data-plane connectivity.\n- Controller connectivity:\n  - All OVS bridges show Controller “tcp:20.0.0.100:6633” is_connected: true.\n  - Switches can ping 20.0.0.100 (RTT ~300–500 ms), suggesting controller responsiveness may be suboptimal but reachable.\n\nData-Plane/Flow Findings\n- leaf_1 (OVS):\n  - fail_mode: secure, controller connected.\n  - Flows: only one flow:\n    - cookie=0x0, table=0, priority=100 actions=drop (counters increasing)\n  - Effect: This wildcard drop at priority 100 causes all packets to be dropped on leaf_1. Explains ARP failures and “Destination Host Unreachable” from hosts on leaf_1.\n- leaf_2 (OVS):\n  - fail_mode: secure, controller connected.\n  - Flows are MAC/port specific but reference in_port/output ports 5 and 6 (eth4/eth5), and ports 3/4, with MACs 5a:33:6d:7c:6a:4b and 6a:7b:7d:33:99:b2.\n  - Actual host-facing ports per topology are eth0 (port 1) for host_2_1 and eth1 (port 2) for host_2_2. There are no installed flows matching ports 1 or 2.\n  - Effect: Traffic from hosts on ports 1/2 does not match any programmed forwarding rules; with secure mode and the current pipeline, packets are not being forwarded, causing intra-leaf and inter-leaf communication failure for host_2_1/host_2_2.\n- spine_1 (OVS):\n  - fail_mode: secure, controller connected.\n  - Flows reference the same MACs seen on leaf_2 and forward between ports 3/4, consistent with a different/incorrect topology view.\n  - Interface stats show TX dropped on eth2 (7557), suggesting additional stress/drops, likely due to misprogrammed paths.\n\nTopology/Mapping Mismatch Evidence\n- leaf_2 flows reference eth4/eth5 (ports 5/6) for hosts, but actual hosts are on eth0/eth1 (ports 1/2).\n- Flows and ARP cache entries refer to MACs for 10.0.0.15 and 10.0.0.16 (host_4_3, host_4_4), which are not part of the described deployment. This indicates the controller is using a topology config intended for a larger environment (e.g., 4-leaf/host_4_x), not the present 2-leaf setup.\n\nLocalization\n- Faulty devices (state):\n  - leaf_1: Flow table contains a blanket drop rule (priority=100 actions=drop) — isolates host_1_1 and host_1_2 entirely.\n  - leaf_2: Flow table programmed for non-existent host-facing ports and irrelevant MACs — host_2_1 and host_2_2 traffic not matched/forwarded.\n  - spine_1: Flow table consistent with the same incorrect controller view; not the origin but participates in the wrong forwarding logic.\n- Control-plane:\n  - Controller is connected to all switches but is pushing incorrect flows and/or missing table-miss/learning logic for the active host-facing ports. RTT to controller is relatively high (300–500 ms), which may exacerbate convergence but is not the main cause.\n\nRoot Cause\n- The SDN controller is operating with an incorrect or stale topology/host inventory and port mapping, likely configured for a larger “leaf_4/host_4_x” environment. As a result:\n  - leaf_1 was programmed with an all-traffic drop entry (priority 100), fully blocking traffic on that leaf.\n  - leaf_2 was programmed with flows for ports 5/6 and MACs of hosts not present in this lab, leaving actual host ports (1/2) without appropriate forwarding rules.\n  - spine_1 flows reflect the same misplaced intent.\nThis control-plane misprogramming directly causes the ARP failures and end-to-end packet loss observed between hosts in the 10.0.0.0/24 subnet.", "generation_info": {"finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 20111, "output_tokens": 4117, "total_tokens": 24228, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 19456}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, "reasoning": 2944}}}
